A table of solstice/equinox dates and full moon dates with
"traditional" moon names,  for 2000 to 2099.  This was
generated with the 'phases.cpp' code in the 'lunar' repository,
and is used by 'lunchart' (code to generate PostScript/PDF
lunar calendars).

I added the names by hand (with some editor tricks to speed that
process up a bit).  I followed the _Maine Farmer's Almanac_
scheme in which full moon names are assigned by season :

Winter:
   After Yule
   Wolf
   Lenten

Spring:
   Egg
   Milk
   Flower

Summer:
   Hay
   Grain
   Fruit

Autumn:
   Harvest
   Hunter's
   Before Yule

Every two or three years,  you get four full moons in a season.
For some reason,  the _Maine Farmer's Almanac_ called the
_third_ moon in that season the 'Blue Moon'.  (The modern concept
in which the second full moon in a Gregorian-calendar month is
called 'blue' is a more modern definition.)

This was discussed and analyzed in two articles in _Sky & Telescope_,
May 1999 and in a follow-up article a few months later than I no
longer have.
